[10] China (Hong Kong): airport and hospital
Date: 3 Apr 2019
Source: Ejinsight [abridged, edited]
http://www.ejinsight.com/20190403-first-measles-case-involving-healthcare-worker-reported/


Four more people were confirmed to have contracted measles in the city, taking the number of such cases this year [2019] to 40.

Three of the 4 new measles patients work at the airport, while the 4th is a radiographer working at Princess Margaret Hospital, according to the Department of Health's Centre for Health Protection (CHP) and the Hospital Authority (HA).

All are males in their 20s with good health records. They are now in stable condition.

This is the 1st time that a healthcare worker has been infected by the measles virus since the current outbreak began, the Hong Kong Economic Journal reported.

According to the CHP, the 23-year-old radiographer, who developed fever and a rash on Mon 1 Apr 2019 before being admitted to the hospital, had not worked in any of the high-risk wards during his communicable period.

He also had no recent travel history, nor did he visit the airport in the past few days.

The 3 other patients include a 23-year-old man who works at the Cathay Pacific Cargo Terminal located at the Hong Kong International Airport, and 2 workers, aged 23 and 29, assigned at Terminal 1. 19 of the 40 measles cases that have been confirmed so far are airport or airline workers.

The Department of Health expects the measles outbreak at the airport to continue in the days ahead, and as such, control measures being implemented there will go on for some time until further notice.

Detailed arrangements will depend on the latest situation and will be announced in due course.

At least 124 people have received measles jabs at the vaccination stations set up at the airport, bringing the cumulative number of vaccinations so far given there to 7645.

Dr. Ho Pak-leung, president of the Carol Yu Centre for Infection at the University of Hong Kong, said on Wed 3 Apr 2019 that it is now certain that a 2nd round of infections has emerged.

